  "prompt": "What is the difference between O- and O+?",
  "response": "The difference between O- and O+ blood types lies in the presence or absence of the Rh factor, a protein found on the surface of red blood cells.\n\n- **O- (O negative)**: This blood type does not have the Rh factor. People with O- blood are considered universal donors because their blood can be transfused to individuals of any blood type. However, O- individuals can only receive blood from other O- donors.\n\n- **O+ (O positive)**: This blood type has the Rh factor present. O+ blood can be donated to anyone with a positive blood type (A+, B+, AB+, O+), but O+ individuals can only receive blood from O+ or O- donors.\n\nIn summary, the key difference is that O- blood lacks the Rh factor, making it more versatile for donations, while O+ blood has the Rh factor, which slightly limits its donation compatibility but expands its receiving options.",
